This photo was taken about a year ago, at a moment when I felt like I was falling apart.
.
I was on a job, and could barely work or talk to my clients. It had never happened to me. You probably have actually never seen me on a job, but I am usually super present, focused and I pay attention to everyone to make sure they feel heard, respected and remembered.
.
I’ve been on both side of the camera so I am aware of all the work it takes to make good stuff. I try to bring the best energy I can. That’s the me I know.
.
And suddenly I was this empty shell. Exhausted and depressed and barely there. And quite ashamed of it. 
But one thing is, I have a very hard time hiding my pain - or my joys. I’m just quite real most the time... Sometimes to a fault.
.
It scared me. I didn’t want people to misunderstand me. Think that I was a thoughtless diva. Never hire me and my team again. So I remember sitting down with @caitlinrvillarreal who works with me and is a wonder and a beautiful human and telling her look, I am so so sorry, but here is what’s happening. I am holding on by a hair. I know I will feel better soon but right now - this is where I am. I wish we could have pushed back this job. But we couldn’t.
.
As a boss that felt terribly vulnerable. I want to be an inspiration, a person you can count on. Not that fragile weepy woman.
.
She said thank you for telling me. Thank you for trusting me. We got your back.
.
I made it through, and we went on and created happy joyful images.
.
I can’t thank the team enough for protecting me and putting a screen of smoke between me and my client.
.
And now I look at this moment, this image taken between two shots and all I can feel is gratitude. For being surrounded by the most wonderful team. For the highs, the lows, and as it ALWAYS happens, the unexpected arms that open up to catch you as you’re falling.
.

This weekend I totally, radically got rid of my clothes. What’s left is mostly jeans, tee-shirts & sneakers. Gonna let this sit for a little bit, and then do another pass.
.
I’ll resell, regift & recycle.
.
Going through all this (I guess Mary Kondo style though I haven’t read her book) is so difficult. We hold on to so much stuff without realizing the weight it carries.
I still had a lot of weird clothes from old fashion weeks even though I my intention is never to go to another fw. It made me giggle (& feel sad for my old self that freaked out about “what to wear” before these) that there are clothes that I could ONLY wear for one type of event - the type where I was trying to be someone else than myself.
.
Clothes that cost so much money that even if I was not wearing them, I wouldn’t want to get rid of them. Twisted - shows how expensive things often own us more than we own them...
.
But also clothes that I bought too fast because they were cheap. Low prices often make us feel like it’s “nothing”: we can buy & think later. We can “return easy!!!” - except we never do because the low price doesn’t incentivize us (a whole industry is built on thoughtless buying - it’s destroying the planet) - think even if you buy cheap!
.
Clothes that I love but that carry so much emotional weight. Hard! That jacket I wore  with that man on that date. That dress I wore when I received that award. This bag I bought with my first big paycheck.
.
Oh, the clothes that “will come back in fashion” - so what, am I waiting to get old enough that fashion will have made a full cycle & I can wear stuff from 20 years ago “hey guys I ACTUALLY SAW DISCO!!!” 👵🏼🤪😂
.
Then there is my essentials - that I wear so much they get old & sad without me seeing it. These are the hardest! I just have to get used to replacing them soon enough. New pair of Rondini, Gucci loafers, Repetto...
.
Was hard! I had to have my sister on the phone yelling “Come on! LET GO!!! You don’t want your closer to look like thrift store!!!” TOUGH LOVE Laetitia 😭
.
So for now it’s going to be jeans & tees until I get inspired again. Yup these earrings in the photo? They’re probably only good in photos 🤗 ahah!!!

I don’t even know where to start to talk to you about sleep - but I know that last week I received so much feedback about my dark room and speaking about my sleep problems that I thought I would try to explore the subject...
.
Let’s start with a few things I have learned:
.
Sleeping issues can go unnoticed for years. For years I just though I was “an early riser” but when I started looking closer, I realized I would be sleeping a five hour night on a regular basis.
.
When you’re used to running on empty, you don’t realize that you are. You get used to having crazy sugar & caffeine cravings (your body needs it to keep moving because it is so exhausted and sugar gives a spike of energy)(hello weight problems!) to have debilitating mood swings (the first thing that lack of sleep impacts is your mental health) and giant crashes where you just sit there and look in the distance like an empty shell. Worse - you can never really rest because your body is in high alert all the time.
.
The stress created by that vicious cycle can make a huge mess in your body. I won’t go into this here - we know stress is the root of most diseases.
.
I remember my sister telling me it was so weird I was not suffering from jet lag. And “How did I do it?”
Well now I know. It’s not that I was not - it’s that I had completely lost touch with what it means to FEEL RESTED. I just kept going even if I was losing myself in the process.
.
So, I guess the first thing, if you want to explore your sleep is to ask yourself if you wake up feeling rested. When I am not sleeping well, i wake up with my brain already rushing and planning and solving problems (I used to think that was cool 😅). When I have slept well, i wake up not even knowing where I am, in a truly happy haze that take a few lovely minutes to dissipate.
.
All right, tell me if you want to know more, because sleep is a big subject and I am quite passionate. But my theory is that if Donald Trump was sleeping well - well he would be Barack Obama 😂 - I just mean that the internal peace you feel when you sleep is SO important that it could literally change nations if we knew how to honor it instead of looking down on it 🙏

I love the desert. There is something about big open skies and emptiness that envelops me and feeds my soul. When I moved to California I knew but I don’t think I understood how close the ocean and the desert where. I didn’t know I would get to hang out with joshua trees and scorpions on a regular basis. .

As I told you before I truly believe in magnetism, energies and recharging through them. Jump in the ocean, walk in a forest, sit in the desert. .

During our hike, we were all chatting and giggling. At some point we sat on warm rocks and Magda @themagdalenaexperience asked that we make a few minutes of silence just to listen to nature. It made me so grateful to be surrounded by people who could understand the beauty and the quality of being silent together - a few minutes of silence can be so much deeper and potent between people than chatting endlessly. .

It was such a lesson for me in not always trying to fill what’s empty. 
No better place to take this in than the desert... .

New York City has become such a stressful environment for me - not just because of the city itself which I still love but because when I come, now, it’s all meetings meetings meetings all over town - no time to chill.

When I started this bicoastal thing I used to overpack my days trying to also see friends, visit new places, and also overpacked my luggage - trying to have an outfit for every occasion.

I don’t anymore. If I want to see my friends, I take an extra day when I can. I take breaks. And I wear easy soft clothes like @stjohnknits that feel cosy and work for every occasion.

Last weekend was magic. I went to visit my friend @themagdalenaexperience in her house in the desert - @desertmilkadobe - She had invited a group of us to come hang out and cook and just be together and the most beautiful moments happened.
.
From making soups to hiking to meditating to making pottery to having a tea ceremony to laughing hard to talking DEEP (my favorite type of conversations) there was a stellar sense of harmony and peace (maybe what inspired my to talk about happiness on Monday!) we didn’t know each other and all came together in such a natural way. .

Magda has created the most beautiful jewel of a house I’ve seen. It’s a dream. It reflects the purity of the desert outside - every single detail is perfect in its beauty. Nothing is extra - yet there is a real sense of comfort and home. .

It made me want to get back to my home and Mary Kondo the crap out of it!!!
.
Here are a few photos - I didn’t post all weekend just because I wanted to take it all in. For moments like that, for such inspiration, love and beauty, I am endlessly grateful.
.

When do you feel happy? .

To me, happiness, like success, is something that we all talk about and all strive for, yet it’s something completely different for each person. And, because we’re not sure what success is but we know we’re supposed to want it, we often accept the general definition without questioning it.
.
It took me a long time to understand what my definition of success is - and it’s not making millions. Once I figured that out - and the many other things that came with it, the pressure could slowly let go. .

Happiness is a moment, not a state. We can’t be continually happy. Happy is like a bird that lands on your shoulder at a moment you weren’t expecting it. And the second you try to capture it, it goes away.
.
The only thing you can do is create a good home for it and forget about it.
.
I am slowly understanding that my sense of happiness comes from a deep feeling of interior peace and connection to my emotions and my needs. When I can feel the big quiet inside, it’s a sign. It can be alone driving, or surrounded by people - it doesn’t matter. It can be in moments of total love and beauty or at moments when my life is falling apart. As long as I am allowing and living my emotions, I connect to the quiet - and i make room for happiness.
.
Unhappiness is : anytime I deny myself my emotions and my needs. .

But that’s just me (and it doesn’t mean living I’m living in my bubble and ignoring other people’s needs 😋)- It takes practice to get to understanding yourself, and discipline to integrate what you know. It’s a lot of the teachings of our retreats (and why we love them so much) (gaaaaah we’re working on the next one!!!) - trying to give our guests the tools to understand themselves and their needs and be independant thinkers.
.
Who am I kidding 😂 I am the number one student of our retreats - which is also why I am so passionate about them. As in most things I’ve explored professionally - they stem from my personal quest, and I share along the way. .

I would love to know - what’s your definition of success? And when do you feel truly happy?

This is my bedroom!
.
Sleep has always been a “thing” for me - I fall asleep easily but tend to wake up too early, any sound or light can wake me up. Also my internal clock is way too precise, meaning I deal with stress while I am sleeping (a lot of us are, if you’re interested I am happy to talk more about it). It’s not cool. I can come back from a party at 4am and wake up at 6, just because it’s my usual wake up time 😑 - And then be exhausted all day long.
.
When I went to see my psychiatrist the first thing he asked me was : how do you sleep?
Yes: sleep is the most important factor for our mental health.
.
SO - the rule when thinking of a bedroom is to keep in mind that it should be used for two things : sleep & sex (yes and yes!!!). Okay reading is fine 🤓 No working no Game Of Thrones no texting (I mean unless your bedroom is also your office, living, & kitchen aka when I lived in my studio in Paris !) - of course, it’s hard. I still bring my screens in my bedroom most days. I still wake up to my phone most days. I bought some blue light blocking glasses and never ever wear them. Ah! But I’m trying -  work in progress.
.
I also wanted to room to be a refuge. LA (and my house!) is all about brightness and sunlight, and sometimes you just want to truly chill down. .
So I used real black out shades from @theshadestore - painted everything in the Dark night shade from @hgtvhomebysherwinwilliams , and had the sheets dyed by @flaneurnyc (such a cool feature they do!) I wanted a totally monochrome bedroom - @sarahshermansamuel had to stop me: I also wanted to put wall to wall carpet in the same shade. We might still end up doing it! I love a good old fashion carpet 😌
.

This is a dream come true. A bathroom just for me, but we could totally have champagne in my bathtub. It’s the place where I bathe, shower & put on my make up, but also where I have solo naked dance parties, sing like if I was - depending on the mood Barbra Streisand, Kendrick Lamar or Chan Marshall. I do a lot of my home exercise in there, I read too.
.
I’ve always been like that with bathrooms. Maybe part of it is my Moroccan culture? They’re a super important part of the house to me... Even if no one really gets to see it. It’s like a bedroom - it’s a reflection of our interior world that not many get to see, yet that’s where the magic happens ☺️
.
I’d been bathroom frustrated for so long!
.
When it was time to think about my first real bathroom @sarahshermansamuel and I went for it.
.
I wanted a lot of space for my beauty products. I didn’t want a double sink - a weird pet peeve of mine, don’t judge - and I dreamt of a vanity because I love to be able to sit down to do my make up & whatever grooming stuff a woman has to do.
.
I of course wanted tile (what’s more beautiful than tile?), and a place as bright as possible, even with a small window. So these light shiny tiles bring that extra glow! Then for stone we chose travertine. It reminded me of interiors of the 80s which I love. I also wanted warm tones - so of course natural untreated wood had to be there.
.
Then ask Sarah about this amazing round mirror because that’s totally her genius. Having someone to source pieces for you is one of the best parts of working with a designer!
.
Mmm what else? I’ll show you more about that room soon. And I have to say I feel incredibly lucky I have a space like that, made just for me. I really do.

This is an important one for me:
.
This book is called The Eye, How The World’s Most Influencial Creative Directors Develop Their Vision. 
I’m part of it. With some of my idols @driesvannoten , Christian Dior, Franca Sozzani & more legendary names.
.
For once in my life, I’m not surprised - I’m honored to be recognized as an important figure, who shaped the world as it is today.
.
It took a long time for me to accept honors. When I got my CFDA award, presented by @pharrell , whom I had invited & had accepted my request (🤪) I thought it was a happy accident. I’m this weird outsider. It’s chance. It’s timing. It was not impostor syndrome. Just “how tf did a girl from Corsica get so lucky”.
.
Yet over the years, I started recognizing the influence of my work.
.
I helped illustration get back. I was one of the first streetstyle photographers, photographing women on the street just the way they were & pushing that new vision of style worldwide. At first, I got so much shit about talking about luxury online. No brand wanted anything to do with it. But to me this was clear. So I created bridges. I was the first blogger to sit front row. It was not easy. Fashion was buttoned up in its safe space. I created a NYT best seller that is translated in 16 languages & is still going strong - after 4 years! Oh also, I’m French - I did all of this in English - yes, even the book.
.
I had no plan. I just did what I believed in.
.
When I saw a new generation of influencers coming - I was so happy I had helped open those doors. A lot of them, to this day, come & thank me. It warms my heart.
.
I take it as an honor when people call me the original. I don’t say “oh nonono please” anymore.
.
So I want to say: enough minimizing ourselves. I’m not in this amazing book by chance. I created this. I’m proud. I am on to my next chapter, but having made a mark is a BIG DEAL. I was a woman with not much else than an eye & an ideal.
.
I still am - so I want to dedicate this post to all you who are struggling to find your voice and opening these bloody doors.
.
Guys, you got this.
.

Depression is a word that is so incredibly scary. And going through one can feel like being in a well with slippery walls. But there are many things we can do to get out of it if we’re willing to look at ourselves differently.
.
When I finally recognized that I was going through a depression, an incredible moment of surrender happened.
.
First it allowed me to be kind and patient with myself. It’s crazy we have to crash so low to finally allow ourselves the most basic kind of self care. 
Then it allowed me to reach out for help and build a solid team around me. I now have a wonderful psychologist and psychiatrist that work together and truly support me. And more. We need guides!
It also allowed me to go through a giant reality check - this I am still going through and probably will keep on healthily going through for the rest of my life. Why do I want things, why do I do things? Which people and situations do I chose to put myself in? Is it because of society’s conditioning? My culture? My emotional history?
.
I have learned to catch myself when I start getting lost in my emotions. 
I feel better than ever, more real & it has nothing to do with outside events (A break up! A house! A cover! Trump!) and everything to do with the work I do inside.
.
I now make my mental health my number one priority before absolutely anything else. I want to keep talking about this and the tools I found because I think so many of us feel lost and have nowhere to turn. Sooooo many of us are depressed and don’t know it. I lived for three years without understanding why it was so damn hard to face each day. Now I wake up excited and filled with wonder.
.
Depression is sometimes unfortunately the best wake up call. It is in darkness that we find the light. Don’t wish for a picture-perfect life - wish for one with depth and self-discovery. Welcome and question your painful moments. When you can’t keep going with the life you’ve created for yourself (wether it looks shiny or shitty from the outside) falling apart can be a gift.
.
Forever grateful I didn’t hold on to the person I was. For with all her borrowed dreams and good intentions, she was killing me.

I really wanted a nook. Like - really. I don’t know why but I think humans are drawn to corners where they can nest themselves. I wanted a big table for (as we say in America) “entertaining” (so Martha of me) but I also have meals on my own, or just with one friend, and didn’t want to be lost on a giant diner table.
.
I wanted both!
.
The thing is that in a modern house with open volumes there are no corners or nooks to be found. You have to create them. As I opened a window in the kitchen (more on that later) I lost a ton of storage space. That’s how the lightbulb came - why not extend the kitchen storage into the dining room and carve a nook out of this?
.
I showed a few images to @sarahshermansamuel and she came up with that magical corner that’s kind of breaking the internet 🤪. The @asplundstore table is a wonder, one of my favorite pieces of furniture.
.
Maybe weird, but I wanted a TV in my kitchen (the only place where I have a TV) (the nook is integrated in the kitchen) to watch @wendyshow while cooking (#kiddingnotkidding)(love you Wendy! Can’t wait to have you back on the show!) and this is the last piece of magic of the nook : the artwork is a TV! Made to look like a piece of art when it’s not in tv mode. You can chose your art and change it whenever you want. I think all TVs should be like that!
.
To finish we chose this natural leather back. It’s going to get stained and change color over the years, but that’s exactly the point 😌
.
The nook became the place where I spend the most time - and the cutest place for long breakfasts, lunch & diner for two and deep talks about life (my favorites) and about what sneakers to wear (my other favorite).
.

One of my house dreams has always been built ins. Wether it’s shelves or sofas or any elements - I just love the permanent, utter groundedness (am I making up words?) they bring to a home. I also love that often they provide real sturdy corners where to nest and hang and drink tea for hours.
.
I also love the softness @sarahshermansamuel brought to all this by creating these beautiful rounded edges on the sides. And that table!!! (Sorry I am a little bit in love with my home) - I wanted to stay away from “too obvious” designer furniture. I have to say, I think in the last ten years mid century modern had taken over the world - and too often badly copied, losing its appeal. I still love it in touches but I wanted to stay away from using it too much, or putting in my home an obvious “this is a *insert famous designer name* piece“ - even if I love these pieces.
.
Looking a bit further helps with budget too. The only trick is to really look around really and have an eye. So when @sarahshermansamuel found that Alessandro Bussana coffee table on @sothebyshome , I was like OH YES.
.
I want to finish this little living room corner tour with the art - I only put my own art in my studio upstairs, but in the house I love to feel inspired by other artists. I had found these @marniegilder years ago and ordered them and then went from apartment to apartment without ever finding the perfect spot to hang them. I was so happy when we finally did!

So how was my retreat at @theranchmalibu ?
.
Intense. The main activity is hiking. Then there is more exercise, yoga, nutrition. It’s really physical. Challenging 4 days...
.
Hike 1: scared. Who are these people? Why am I here? Let’s go on a hike. Meet people. Test out gear (yes sports gear gets real when you’re actually doing sport with it 😂). Ok people are nice. This is pretty but we’ve been hiking for 2 hours and a half. Can we go back?
.
H2 : excited & challenged. I got this. Easy! WTF - this elevation is intense!!! I’m hot, sweaty, and I... Oh the view is stunning! I love this! Hiking is my new passion. Muscles are sore. But I just walked 11 miles at a fast pace - I’m a hero.
.
H3 : woop, let’s go! And... eeeh okay. Am I bored? Ok one foot in front of the other. Listen to music (not recommended) and just do it, dreaming about lunch. .
Interlude: 1400 calories / day at that level of exertion can sound crazy - but the food was so nutritious i wasn’t hungry. Taught me so much about real food and portions! Real ones! Not the gigantic plates we eat usually. Reminded me about pleasure. Of eating when you’re hungry. Of having just one bite.  My body was saying thank you. .
H4 : no. Nonono. Is it raining? Eeeeeeh it’s LA rain. It’s nothing! Oh no. Nonono. It’s pouring. I’m damp. Freezing. I’m hiking in a cloud I can’t see anything. I am alone. Do I have my walkie? Yes okay. I want a bath. I want a coffee. I want my mooooom!!! Why am I here!? Been hiking for 3 hours in slushy mud. I hate this. I am going to fall and die. I’m too far to go back. Wait.  What if... I enjoyed the rain on my face, found a way to de-freeze my hands and go with the challenge? Go, breathe, do it. You’re safe. Go beyond. .
That hike became the best one - quite cathartic. I like that the guides didn’t shy away from the rain and mud and let us go. That’s knowledge and courage. 
I came back home with a clarity I haven’t felt in months. It’s not about the retreat itself, but the retreat pushed me to get out of myself and my ways. How often do we have the chance to do that? .
And to just walk, alone, on a healthy high, in the beautiful, beautiful nature?

Peace...
.
And yes, totally! California and Corsica have so much in common, as you keep noticing. The weather, the palm trees, the mountains, the beaches - even the bushes look and smell like the Maquis - but the vibes are entirely different to me.
.
Not going to go into a talk about magnetism right now at 7am 😂 but I totally believe that places have their own vibes. I have a running list of my favorite “vibing” places if that’s of any interest to you - totally subjective alright 🤪
.
Anyway so, right now, the California vibes, kind, warm, embracing, are exactly what I need. Have a wonderful day ☀️

So now, I try to catch myself. I find ways to get out of my mind. 
And to do that, the body is the best path. The more I move my body, the more I realize how much my body needs to move... And to be in nature. I sweat, I breathe, my worries dissolve, I take in the beauty of the world, I quite literally gain perspective. Sleep comes back, thoughts rearrange and peace, and love - they rise again. 
While this retreat is a real challenge - check my stories if you want to see a little bit more - , it’s also a great way to remember how simple, so bloody simple it is to feel happy : sleep, move a lot, eat well. It’s been doing wonders and I am only starting the third day!

Be radical*
.
I used to beat myself up so much about the things that didn’t make me feel good. The people, the remarks, the comments, or even Instagram accounts I used to follow to “stay informed” but that would make me feel a bad taste in my mouth each time I would open it. .
I beat myself up because I have always wanted to be a loving, understanding, kind, curious person. I wanted to understand all cultures (I even tried to stick to watching one full season of the Kardashians to try to “get it”!!!)(I don’t. But it’s ok, some people do and if it’s their jam then good!)
.
And then one day I started to understand how much this way of thinking was hurting me. Many friendships where hurtful and empty, some aspects of our culture would get to me in a frightening way, and my social media feeds (which sometimes I think is a miniature version of what we let in in our life) would literally hurt my eyes and my heart. .
Slowly I became radical. Being radical to me means being able to say no without justifying or intellectualizing. It’s hard. It’s really hard. The hardest is to let go of relationships. Wooof! Hard. I started unfollowing anything that didn’t make me happy to follow, without rationalizing - bad feeling = unfollow, no judgment on myself (I now follow more @natgeo stuff, funny memes and friends than anything else). I decided to consciously choose my sources of information and subscribed to the @nytimes because it is important to pay for good information even if you don’t read a tenth of it. Oh, and I block anyone that leaves unconstructive nasty comments. I unsubscribe to any newsletter i didn’t invite in my mailbox. Etc, etc, etc. .
You get it. 
Few years of this and my life is completely, entirely, incredibly softer. And I feel that, without all this unnecessary irritants all around me, I am actually a kinder, curious and more understanding person, the way I wanted to be. But I am also a radical, and it doesn’t mean I am an asshole - it just means that you can’t be soft, vulnerable and open if you’re not also very chivalrous about protecting yourself... . * Now about that word radical, keep reading in the coms...

How able am I to truly listen?
Probably not so much. Listening is not just the act of keeping silent while someone is speaking, to then placate your point of view and your stories on them.
.
Listening is opening yourself completely without trying to change, give advice or project anything on what someone is saying - or trying to show who you are and bring everything back to you. It’s softening a lot. It’s not easy. And of course, the more intimate, the more precious the relationship - the more difficult.
I wonder why we’re not taught these things at school. The art of listening should be a sacred life tool!
.
Having a podcast is teaching me a lot about this art as a form. But more than anything as usual, well, the deep teaching comes from all the mistakes I have made, in the line of what Maya Angelou said “When someone shows you who they are, believe them.” To me it could be “when people tell you who they are, listen to them.” Because if we listen, they really do.
.
I am trying to become better at listening. And I am trying to start by listening to myself. Meditation is helping finding that softness and openness and find the answers inside.
.
When I meet you, I really hope I am able to listen to you.

H o n o r  T i m i n g
.
Three or four years ago, probably thanks to my burn out, I started to feel that something was off inside me.
.
I was still unaware of what was going on, I just knew that if I kept going, something inside me would die.
.
Well. 
In today’s culture we often talk about “epiphanies” and “life changing moments”, describe a new belief, diet, supplement, drug as a source of profound change, as if change and self discovery could happen in just a moment.
. 
I did think that too. I had this kind of magical thinking that something or someone would happen and save me and... Do the work for me. 
Wrong, of course. What I call my burn out happened more than three years ago and only now am I starting to feel some true change.
.
In the mean time, I did a ton of therapy, saw shamans, healers, started new practices, dropped them, made so many mistakes, felt discouraged, let people think I was a bit crazy, had no idea where I was going and what was so wrong with me. There were so many moments when I would be like yesssss this is it, I got it!!! Only to get back to painfully normal a few days later. .
And I finally learned there are no short cuts. The journey is the bloody way. I even learned to make peace with pain and embrace it. .
So, yes, our Chile retreat changed our lives. Yes, yoga, meditation changed my life. Yes, a few people changed my life. But they are just beautiful (or painful?) moments on a life journey. .
It truly made me believe in the genius of trusting and letting ourselves lean softly in the arms of life. Things happen at the right time. People show up when you’re ready. We never get “there”. My timing is slow. I am a late bloomer. I need to learn by experience. Books are great, but to me, they are not enough. I need to honor the timing. 
So now, I am done with forcing things. Omg DONE!!! 😂
.
And I am practicing not to wait while I am waiting - but to cultivate and live fully every moment. And it’s really hard, but the answer is: practice. If what you’re waiting for is not happening yet it is because, probably, something else needs your attention. .
Maybe yourself? .
I know that was (is?) my - very humbling - case.

These last years have been bumpy to say the least. I’ve opened up about it. What’s funny is that when I look back, I started these years in this mirage of the fashion girl, living the “high life” (dumb expression). Truth is, after a few years of exploring that world, I became miserable and I felt very far from myself.

Except I had no idea of who I was. 
So I tried to stay the person I knew. Even if I was agonizing. 
That’s when life starting getting hard, and harder, brutalizing me into letting go of that old self I was so attached to. 
In 2018, it came crumbling down - until finally, a flower started growing again on the ashes.

When I see this photo, shot by my sister, who was there every moment even when she didn’t get what the fuck I was doing, when I see myself with no make up, wearing whatever clothes... When I see myself feeling so at home in nature - me who ended up being so crushed by the buildings of NYC... When I see this photo of me, here in Corsica where I grew up learning to chat (like literally have conversations) with nature... When I see it I can hear my sister saying “sit here - I have to take a photo, look at this, it’s the Tree of Life” and i thought of the medal engraved of a Tree of Life I am wearing that I bought in a church store when I was so sad I sat and prayed... When I see it I remember when, a few months ago, I made the promise to myself to live in my truth whatever the consequences. 
And life started flowing again.

When I see it, I wouldn’t change anything. I want to thank 2018 (17, 16) for the lessons.

And thank the woman I was, who did nothing but her best - and is still here inside (and still wants to steal my sister’s Balenciaga sneakers). In this moment, to me, nature, quiet and conversing with the trees is essential.

Might be completely different to you. 
Allow yourself to love what you love, grow, fuck up, and to change, even if the world around you resists it. People will always judge. Change is hard, but it is wonderful - ask the butterflies!

I love Instagram because I love pretty images but I also hate Instagram because of pretty images. Because « pretty » can become a prison.
. 
A bright, colorful, smiling photo will almost always get more likes than a dark, imperfect, real photo. . 
For any creator it is a curse. Imagine any artist creating with “likes” in mind? How many major works of art would have been turned into “pretty” instead of challenging, deep, thought-provoking?
. 
How many messages would have been transformed into just a punchline?
. 
I have always been afraid of numbers. Statistics and numbers. Gah! They’re the enemy of my creativity. They often kill it.
. 
When “likes” appeared, I don’t think anybody knew what tyranny they would become. Because we’re all human. We’re made of emotions. I don’t know one person who can honestly say she doesn’t get a boost the more likes she gets.
. 
I wish Instagram would come up with a way to opt out of numbers. To have a version of it as an option that wouldn’t show you the number of followers of one person, the numbers of likes and not count the number of comments.
. 
You would be able to chose what option you prefer. If you like counting your likes, go at it.
. 
But if you’re like me and don’t like having numbers thrown at your face all day long, good or bad - you would just switch numbers off and Instagram could become what I see in it, a fascinating platform for self expression.
. 
This system would have traps too - but at least it would be a start?
. 
I know Instagram implemented changes in terms of controlling the time we spend on it - but I honestly don’t believe in this at all.
. 
It’s, again, putting all the responsibility and guilt on the user, treating us as addicts... Which we probably are.
. 
I believe in making people’s emotional lives easier, not more complicated. I believe we can create tools that bring us more freedom. And I really believe it’s time to take mental health seriously.
. 
I would love to hear your thoughts on this!
#gdmentalhealthjourney

It’s so interesting how we lose touch with ourselves - it starts by wanting to please others : our parents, our friends, our followers or whatever we imagine society demands of us - and slowly we lose the sense of play.
. 
Recently I have shared my mental health journey and understood through the feedback I got how much it is sort of everyone’s problem too. So I want to try to share a little more about my journey here. . 
And I want to start with play.
. 
As you know I am an illustrator and an artist’s journey is a quite beautiful but complicated one. And it’s fine! What’s not fine is when the demands we put on ourselves end up stifling our sense of play. I haven’t taken the time to lose time creating and making stuff just for me for years. Making “ugly” or “weird” stuff is as important as making pretty stuff - if we only try to do what we know, the source dries up and we end up just copying ourselves and losing the juice.
. 
Lately, I’ve started making time again to have fun with shapes and color. It would be nothing for child to play and have fun and not give a damn - but it’s a huge step for me. So, here you go, here is a blue clementine. Happy Sunday!

I love the sun. I was born in Corsica, under the sun and I moved to California for the sun. But, CRAP, what a conundrum!
.
There is no way to do “sun” right.
.

Sunscreens either have chemicals or make you look like a ghost. They also damage the oceans, which is terrible and has me thinking twice of what products I put on before I go for a swim. But then, don’t use them and you’ll end up with crappy looking skin or skin cancer. BUT you also need your D vitamin and you need it for real, as in no sunscreen and no sunglasses unless you want to become depressed and, I don’t know, cursed on three generations?
.

Also who can really say they put sunscreen on the back of their hands after each time they wash their hands? Not me.
.

In California, some women who are really worried about their skin succeed in staying absolutely white. They have dark tinted windows on their cars, spf driving gloves and when they walk their dogs, they are fully covered and wear weird hats that look like bees keeper hats. It’s like a sun ghost was passing near you.
.

SO.
.

I decided to give up. Whatever!!! There is no way to be perfect. I try to protect myself when I can, how I can. I try to be conscious of the environment and to not go in the water covered in sunscreen. I try to be fine with the new “freckles” on my arms. I love being outdoors, hiking, swimming, riding my bike, walking my dogs (yes!!!) and even if I often favor a long sleeve over a spaghetti strap, I just keep it as easy as possible.
.

How do you manage this, depending on where you live? What are your favorite sunscreens?

Last week I wrote a post about my recent struggles with - let’s just go ahead and say the word - depression. Since then I received so many messages from all around the world from women saying thank you. Women saying they never felt free to share that. Women feeling like they don’t have a right to say that deep down, they feel like they’re falling apart - while keeping their life and their loved ones all tended to.
.
We shouldn’t have to say thank you for this. It’s time to open up the conversation. Our lives can look fabulous from the outside - it sometimes is totally disconnected to how we feel inside.
.

Mental health is, above everything : HEALTH. It’s not about the sum of our achievements. It’s not about “having it all”. It’s not about saying “I am so blessed I don’t feel the right to complain”.
.
Do you sleep well? Do you deal with panic attacks? Do you have anxiety? Do you sometimes feel like you’re drifting? Do you feel like you’re never good enough? Do you feel constantly overwhelmed, exhausted, “emotional”? Do you feel like you didn’t chose whatever is happening to you? Does social media make you feel like crap?
.
The lists of symptoms is long, and it’s better to not ignore and bury them - because they might not go away with just a shrug or a sunny vacation in an instagrammable place. There are solutions. And not treated, they might keep adding up until they knock you down for good if you don’t take care of yourself.
.
So, let’s open up that conversation. I feel extremely responsible, being somewhat visible on social media with all my traveling and my pretty clothes and pretty photos. I want to be a conscious, well rounded, responsible woman who understands the messages she puts out there do carry weight.
.
You can go read the post following the link in bio, but most of all, go read the comments on it. They are so telling, so real, so honest. So thank YOU for sharing your real emotions.
.
We’re all in this together. 
A huge hug to you my brothers and sisters.
#gdhealthjourney

A little love story:
.
Women Who Run With The Wolves is one of my favorite books. I’ve carried it inside me since I was 26 when a friend, seeing how lost I was trying to please everyone but myself, recommended it. The book helped me say fuck it, I’m going to listen to that voice inside and change my life. Recognizing i should honor the wild woman inside me.
.
I remember at that time being sort of ashamed of my attraction to woo woo things like that, and asking the old bearded, very serious looking man who sold me the book : this is no hippie shit, right? 
And him answering: no, this is very serious shit. Read it.
.

Years later I met Chris and saw that book on his bookshelf. I had lost it in my many moves and finding it was almost like suddenly finding myself. Once again, i was lost at that time, trying to please everyone but myself. I immediately opened it to dive into Clarissa Pinkola Estes marvelous, freeing world.
.

And as I opened it, I saw this wonderful dedication.
.
I was already in love with Chris, so I cracked a smile.
.
See, today, after years of rejecting the dreamer, esoteric, stargazer, wild woman side of me... I now slowly am living it, owning it (I would never have wrote that story even a year ago) feeling fuller and truer than I’ve ever been.
.
And that woman I’m becoming, she knows how to see signs!!! :)
.
PS to Frank, Chris’s brilliant stepfather : you’re just awesome. Men, woman, read, and reread the book. Even if you’re not ready to, leave it in a corner of your room. One day it will fall in your lap and its meaning will jump at you, and possibly, free you...

So, that french thing… Anytime I talk about being healthy (like these last days, trying to go without sugar) or exercise, at some point someone always tells me to stop becoming so American and stay a little bit French, relax and have a glass of wine.
.
It’s interesting, because I think it’s a misconception that all that French women do is to “relax and have a glass of wine”. They’re actually as concerned with their health as any other women, and sometimes as obsessive. A few cultural factors help, like regular meals and cooking at home are more of a thing, food quality is slightly different, but overall, we talk about our abs and our tights too. There is actually a real and exciting health movement in France as well!.
.

So don’t worry, I’m still very French but I also really like my newer American influences. And trying to be a little more healthy doesn’t mean that I’m becoming a health nut. It’s all about finding balance and allowing ourselves to change and evolve, in America or in France, no? .
Also, thank you for all your encouragement to all the international “health nuts”, I’ve been learning so much from your comments! #healthychoices #justtryingtobemyself

This is Chris standing on a cliff, in the place where I grew up. It's a special place in Corsica where nature is highly protected. The air is pure, the water is crystal clear and you're not allowed to fish, dive, or build in some places, as you can see from the photo. You can't have a swimming pool. The list is long. It should be one of the cleanest places on earth, yet after a big storm, our beaches would be absolutely covered in trash and plastic. We would spend days cleaning, knowing that it was just a small thing we could do to help but keeping at it. The thing is, nature doesn't have frontiers, and we're all in this together. And what's happening right now is driving me absolutely crazy and making me very sad, but I hope it will push all of us towards more personal responsibility and action so we can turn a negative into a positive. I really hope...

I got a hot spring bath after that and I thought I was in heaven.

I don't think at any point I had pictured this could happen. Maybe I watch too many American movies with a happy ending. Last night, Chris and I didn't know what to do. He was pacing, I was curled under the sheets, unable to sleep but wanting desperately to wake up to a brighter day.
Then I heard Chris in the middle of the night. 
That's it, he won, he said. 
In my sleep, my heart ripped appart.
My vision of a progressive world, where women and men are finally equals, where racism is a thing of the past, where people of all color and religion and sexual orientation come together in a respectful way, where we work together to change a world and make it a place of healing, of care and attention for others and for our poor planet, that vision just broke down in million pieces at my feet.

What did people say yesterday?
That they are afraid. 
I have a few people in my life that vote for Trump. Or Le Pen, in France. I didn't chose them to be like that, but they are and I listen to them. They're not the devil. They're good people. I swear they're good people! What they feel is powerless. They feel forgotten. They feel like they've given everything for a system that left them lacking, poor, empty.
They've been made to believe the answer is force, ejection, walls.

And why had I not imagined this could happen? Because I live behind closed walls too. The walls of my life, of my social media feeds, catered by me for me with the help of crazy algorithms that make it almost impossible to get a wider view of the world, presenting to me a landscape that conforms to my beliefs... But that is an absolute illusion. 
And today, it's time to wake up from the dream.

These people I know, nothing I'll say will make them change. 
There is only one thing to do. Keep loving them. And live and act on my beliefs like I've never done before.

If fear prompted that disaster, then let's not be fearful. Lets stop building walls. Lets look at each other and not fear the truth. Let's cultivate hope, care, compassion, and responsibility. Lets look around us and take each other's hands. Let's inspire and forgive. 
Let's hope for an American movie happy ending, soon, soon enough.
